    "notes": "Pacific Auto Center (independent used dealer, Fontana CA; stock 61116). The SECOND XSE on your board and a near-twin of c14 — but better-optioned and better-documented. CarGurus lists the vehicle at $35,995; with $736 delivery to Millbrae + $85 doc the all-in is ~$36,816 (CarGurus badges it a 'Great Deal,' $3,226 below their market; CARFAX History-Based Value is $37,670, so it's ~$1,675 below CARFAX value and rated 'Great Value' / 'Well Maintained').\n\nFIT — FULLY LOADED (10/10 tracked features): panoramic glass roof + power sunroof, heated front seats + heated leather steering wheel (XSE Weather Pkg), 8-way power LEATHER (SofTex) memory seats, and — unlike c14 — a PREMIUM SOUND SYSTEM (JBL), plus 360° Surround View + Bird's Eye View, 12.3\" digital cluster, front/rear parking assist w/ auto-braking (ICS), Qi charging, dual-zone A/C. Power liftgate isn't itemized in the listing but comes with the XSE Advanced Technology Package this car carries (confirm in person). This is the only car besides the c13 Limited to hit all 10 of your tracked features.\n\nHISTORY — the standout: CARFAX 1-owner, clean title (DMV-guaranteed, no brands), NO accidents/damage, and EIGHT service records — all at one Toyota store (Norm Reeves Toyota San Diego): 5k/10k/20k services, regular oil changes, a brake-fluid flush (09/30/2025). CARFAX badges 'Regular Oil Changes' + 'Well Maintained.' Prior use = PERSONAL LEASE (lease return; one San Diego driver). LOW miles for the history — 44,600 on a 2023 (in service 12/2022) ≈ 13,679 mi/yr, which CARFAX flags as BELOW the 15k industry average — so no mileage flag here (vs c14's amber ~16.3k/yr).\n\n*** Things to weigh: (1) 1 OPEN RECALL (CARFAX) — free Toyota fix; the card can't flag recalls, so don't forget it — have Pacific clear it, or schedule it locally after delivery. (2) DEALER + LOGISTICS RISK — Pacific Auto Center is an independent (non-Toyota) used dealer with a mediocre 3.0/5 CarGurus rating (124 reviews), and the car sits in SoCal: you'd be buying largely sight-unseen with a $736 delivery to Millbrae (or drive south to inspect). Get an independent PPI and confirm the open recall + power liftgate before you commit; their disclaimer also adds an unspecified electronic-filing charge on top of the $85 doc. (3) Basic warranty expired; not CPO (powertrain 5/60k still has ~15k mi of buffer — more than c14's ~11k).\n\nc14 vs c15 — your two XSEs, head to head: c15 is the better CAR — ~4,400 fewer miles, a much lower ~13.7k mi/yr, EIGHT service records vs c14's TWO, the full 10/10 kit INCLUDING JBL (c14's sticker shows 6 speakers), and a hair cheaper all-in (~$36,816 vs c14's ~$37,112). c14 is the better TRANSACTION — local (San Jose, 25 mi), a reputable franchised Toyota dealer you can walk into and inspect today, and no open recall. Net: if the vehicle/history/equipment matter most, c15 wins; if a low-risk, inspect-it-today, reputable-dealer purchase matters most, c14 wins. Both 4/5.\n\nExpert 4/5: arguably the best-documented, best-equipped non-Limited on your board — 10/10 features, an 8-record single-Toyota-store history, low ~13.7k mi/yr, clean 1-owner, below CARFAX value. Held back from 5 by the open recall, the independent 3.0/5 dealer + ship-sight-unseen logistics, the lease return, and the expired basic warranty. If you're willing to PPI/inspect in SoCal (or trust the delivery + a return window), this edges c14 on the vehicle itself. (Listing photos date to early March 2026 — ~3.5+ months old by late June, so it's likely a long-standing listing: that's negotiation leverage, lead low.)",
