    "notes": "CarMax (stock 70022154), ships $149 from CarMax San Gabriel Valley/Duarte (SoCal) to San Mateo (94401), est. arrival 6/29–7/5. No-haggle $37,998 (CarMax dropped it $1,000 on 06/21/2026 'to match current market'; was $38,998); ZERO doc fees, 10-day money-back return + 30-day/1,500-mi warranty + 125-point inspection. Fully loaded XSE — but read the history before you fall for the equipment.\n\n*** THE HEADLINE — CarMax discloses a 'PRIOR THEFT HISTORY' on this vehicle (its own 'Prior use' disclosure). That means it was reported stolen and recovered. The mitigants: AutoCheck shows a CLEAN title, NO accidents/damage, NO insurance total-loss, and CarMax's 125-point inspection passed — so it was recovered without being totaled or branded. But a theft record is material: (a) it depresses RESALE value and follows the car permanently, (b) theft-recovery cars can carry hidden damage (forced ignition/locks, stripped or swapped parts, interior) even with a clean title, and (c) it can complicate insurance. A car with this flag should sell at a DISCOUNT to clean-history cars.\n\n*** THE PRICING PROBLEM: instead, at $37,998 + $149 ship = ~$38,147 all-in, this is the MOST EXPENSIVE XSE on your board — ABOVE the two clean-history XSEs (c14 ~$37,112 all-in; c15 ~$36,816). You'd pay a premium for the one car with a theft record — backwards. Only pursue it if CarMax discounts it well below c14/c15 to price in the theft, AND an independent PPI (focused on ignition/locks/electrical + prior-repair signs) comes back clean. CarMax's 10-day return is a real safety net for exactly that check.\n\nWhat's genuinely good (why it's not a flat pass on the car itself): equipment is FULLY LOADED — 10/10 tracked features incl. JBL Sound System, Panoramic Sunroof, heated front seats + heated steering wheel, memory/power seats, power hatch, blind-spot + cross-traffic + parking sensors, CarPlay/Android Auto. AutoCheck = SINGLE owner, Vehicle Usage = PERSONAL (better than c14/c15's lease returns), clean title, no accidents. 6 service records (regular oil changes, 40k service done, battery + brakes done 07/2025). Average ~14k mi/yr (42,030 over 3 yrs, in service 07/2023) — BUT the recent stretch was heavy: ~20k mi added between 07/2025 (21,661 mi) and 06/2026 (42,030) with no service recorded in that window. Powertrain warranty has the most buffer of the XSEs (~18k mi left).\n\nOTHER FLAGS: 2 OPEN SAFETY RECALLS — 25TA08 (instrument/combination meter may go blank) and 25TA13 (rearview camera image may freeze) — both remedies available, free at any Toyota dealer; have them cleared. Plus AutoCheck logs Service Bulletin 25TD01 — 'rear traction-motor cable corrosion' on AWD hybrids — a limited service campaign; confirm it was performed. Lien reported (normal, financed). Not Toyota CPO.\n\nExpert 2/5: mechanically it's a clean-title, personal-use, fully-loaded XSE with decent service and CarMax's return safety net — but the CarMax-disclosed PRIOR THEFT HISTORY, paired with the HIGHEST price of any XSE on your board and 2 open recalls, makes it a poor BUY as listed. Recommend PASS unless CarMax knocks the price clearly under the clean c14/c15 (theft-history cars belong at a discount) AND a PPI is clean. For a fully-loaded XSE you actually want, c15 (clean, JBL + pano, 8 records, cheaper) is the far better pick; c14 (local, reputable, inspect today) is the safer one. Re-rate only if the price drops to reflect the history.",
