    "notes": "*** The only BRAND-NEW option on the board — a 2026 RAV4 XLE Premium you're weighing against the used cars (NOT bought or ordered; this is a dealer spec/quote from One Toyota of Oakland, VIN 2T36CRAVXTW061940, stock 263412). Worth tracking now because the 2026 is reaching dealers SOONER than the ~3-month wait you'd assumed — so it's a live option today, not a far-off one.\n\nSPEC: all-new 6th-gen 2026 redesign — 2.5L hybrid AWD now making 236 net hp (up from 219), 45 city / 38 hwy / 41 combined MPG, Toyota Safety Sense 4.0, 12.3\" digital cluster + 10.5\" multimedia. Ruby Flare Pearl / Black SofTex. Optioned with the Weather Package (heated leather steering wheel + rain-sensing/de-icer wipers), XLE Driver Assist Package (front cross-traffic alert, lane-change assist, traffic-jam assist, driver monitor), Panoramic Moonroof Package (panoramic glass roof + power tilt/slide moonroof + digital rearview mirror w/HomeLink), premium paint, and all-weather floor + cargo liners.\n\nFEATURE FIT — 9/10 tracked: it has the panoramic roof, heated seats + heated wheel, 8-way power driver seat, power liftgate, smart key, immobilizer — everything you track EXCEPT JBL. XLE Premium ships a 6-speaker system (JBL is reserved for the XSE Tech package / Limited), and it lacks the XSE's memory + power passenger seat. So on your comfort checklist it matches the c14 XSE (also 9/10, no JBL) and trails the fully-loaded c15/c16/c17 XSEs (10/10, with JBL) on audio only.\n\nPRICE — the catch: $37,500 base + $3,350 factory packages + $339 port + $1,595 delivery = $42,784 advertised; add ~$85 doc ≈ $42,869 all-in (before CA sales tax ~$4.2k + registration — which apply to the used cars too). That makes it the MOST EXPENSIVE option on your entire board — ~$6,050 more than the best-value used XSE (c15, ~$36,816 all-in), ~$5,750 over c14, and about level with the on-hold c17 ($42,297). For that premium you get: 0 miles, a fresh FULL factory warranty (Basic 3/36, Powertrain 5/60, Hybrid 8/100, Battery 10/150) + ToyotaCare 2yr/25k free maintenance, the newest redesign (more power, better MPG, TSS 4.0), your exact color/spec, and ZERO history risk — no theft/accident/mileage/owner unknowns (the only car here that literally can't carry those flags).\n\nTHE DECISION it forces: is a loaded used 2023 XSE worth buying instead of this new one? c15 saves ~$6k AND adds JBL + memory seats + sportier XSE styling — but it's a 3-yr-old lease return with 44k miles and a partly-used warranty. The new one costs ~$6k more but is flawless, newest-gen, fully warrantied, and spec'd to taste. Now that the 2026 is available sooner than expected, that ~$6k delta is the crux: only a genuinely standout used deal (spotless history, well under c15's price, or a must-have you can't get new like JBL) beats just buying new.\n\nExpert 4/5: the safest, newest, zero-risk, exactly-your-spec choice at a fair MSRP — docked one point only because it's the priciest option on the board (~$6k over a comparable used XSE) and, as an XLE Premium, misses the JBL audio the used XSEs have. If the early arrival holds and you value warranty + newest-gen + peace of mind over saving ~$6k, this is your pick; if value dominates, c15 is the one to seriously weigh against it.",
